      <h1>A Simple Retrieval</h1>
      <p class="chapter-label">Chapter One</p>
    </header>

    <div class="excerpt-body">
      <p class="opening">The campfire burned low in the heart of the Whispering Woods, where the Sundering's scars still bled magic into twisted bark and moss-covered stone. The air tasted of copper. The old order of magic had broken, and some places had never healed.</p>

      <p>Anya sat with her back to a moss-slick stone, dark hair tied back with worn leather so it would not catch on blade or branch. Her dagger moved against the whetstone in a steady rhythm, Greygate steel over mountain grit, soft enough not to carry. Firelight caught the pale scar along her jaw each time her gaze shifted. Tree line, path, hollow beneath the roots. Three ways out. Always three.</p>

      <p>Across the fire, Bjorn set another branch where it would catch and hold. Old burn scars silvered his knuckles. His forge-trained hands moved with practiced care, as if flame were another material to be worked. His axe rested within reach, its rune-script holding the dull glow of banked coals.</p>

      <p>Elara had gone still beside the fire, silver-blond braid lying neat over one shoulder despite the road. One hand rested half-curled in her lap. The ward around the camp was almost complete, a thin gold shimmer drawn through damaged threads of the Weave, the hidden pattern of force and connection beneath ordinary sight. The woods resisted her. Old damage set the threads askew. Each correction left an ache behind her knuckles. A few loose strands curled near the delicate point of one ear, but her posture remained Academy-straight.</p>

      <p>She pulled the last strand into place and let out a slow breath, flexing her fingers under her sleeve.</p>

      <p>Bjorn reached for the kettle and shifted it closer to her side of the fire before the water had fully warmed. He did not look at her when he did it. He simply adjusted the little iron hook, settled the pot where the heat would catch it faster, and returned his hand to his knee.</p>

      <p>Anya's whetstone slowed once against the dagger's edge.</p>

      <p>“Useful ward,” she said. “Useful tea.”</p>

      <p>Elara glanced from the kettle to Bjorn, then back to the pale gold shimmer holding around them. “I try to contribute across disciplines.”</p>

      <p>Bjorn's forge-blackened beard, bound in two iron rings, moved with what might have been the beginning of a smile.</p>

      <p>Tonight's task should have been almost mundane. Retrieve a stolen relic from goblin raiders nesting in forgotten temple ruins.</p>

      <p>“The goblins will be deep in their cups by now,” Anya said, her voice barely above a whisper. She tested the edge of her blade against her thumb. “Their kind celebrate every successful raid like it might be their last, drunk, careless, and dreaming of easier prey.”</p>

      <p>Bjorn grunted acknowledgment, his grip tightening slightly on the axe haft. The weapon hummed with barely audible harmonics, steel remembering the songs that had shaped it in the deep forges. “Let them drink themselves into stupors. It'll make the work quicker.”</p>

      <p>“Gently,” Elara said. “Ancient relics are temperamental things. Blood, force, careless intent... any of it may be enough to wake the wrong protection.”</p>

      <p>They left before dawn, and the woods noticed.</p>

      <p>Anya marked a split birch with the point of her dagger when they passed it, a habit older than trust. Ten minutes later the same mark waited ahead of them on the wrong side of the path, fresh sap shining dark in the cut. She stopped without raising a hand. Bjorn stopped because she had. Elara closed her eyes and felt the ward around them pull slightly out of shape, as if the threads had been combed by fingers too large to see.</p>

      <p>“We keep moving,” Anya said.</p>

      <p>Bjorn's axe answered from his back with one low note. The sound did not come from the blade. It came from under the roots.</p>

      <p>At dawn, they reached the ruins. Anya took the outer sentry with one hand over his mouth and one silent cut. No sound reached the courtyard. Then she stopped. The goblins beyond were not drunk. They were not sleeping off their revelry in careless heaps. They clustered at the courtyard's far wall in a tight, miserable mass, a dozen of them, awake and frightened, keeping deliberate distance from the inner sanctum. One rocked with both hands clamped over his ears. Another whispered numbers under his breath in a language Anya did not know and did not like hearing from a goblin mouth. Their shadows leaned toward the sanctum instead of away from the dawn. She held her position and signed back at Bjorn. <em>Wait.</em> He was already moving. She watched him stop with visible effort.</p>

      <p>Elara pressed her hand flat against the nearest threshold stone. The wards were alive in a way the campfire assessment had not predicted. The fresh blood had reached the outer seal. The ward-threads pulled tight, reorienting around the violence at the sentry line. They read it as aggression toward the sanctum, not as service to clearing it. If Bjorn went through the front now, the inner protections would seal.</p>

      <p>“The wards are misreading us,” she said, barely above breath. “They think we are here to take what is inside by force. The direct path closes if we trigger them now.”</p>

      <p>Bjorn's jaw set. His eyes went to the clear courtyard, the direct line to the sanctum door. Everything in his posture said <em>through</em>.</p>

      <p>“East colonnade,” Elara said. “The warding is thinner there. Give me two minutes.”</p>

      <p>Bjorn's grip tightened once around the axe haft. Then he abandoned the direct line to the sanctum and moved for the colonnade without another word, making enough noise to hold the goblins' attention. Anya dissolved back into shadow, circling to cut off any retreat.</p>

      <p>Bjorn drove into the main goblin force, his war-cry echoing off ancient stones as his axe cut a hard path through them. The cluster came apart, frightened creatures in sudden motion, colliding, dropping weapons they had forgotten they held.</p>

      <p>Anya was already at the east gate when the first of them reached it. The retreat collapsed inward. The rest milled between Bjorn's advance and the sanctum wall they had spent the night refusing to touch. There was nowhere good left to run.</p>

      <p>Then Bjorn took one step toward the sanctum.</p>

      <p>The ward struck him before his boot fully settled.</p>

      <p>White light snapped from the threshold to the iron in his greaves, hard enough to ring metal and drive him to one knee. The chamber answered with a low, grinding note. Dust sifted from the cracked ceiling. The goblins shrieked and pressed themselves farther from the sanctum wall.</p>

      <p>“Not him,” Elara said, reading the pattern as it tightened. “The violence. The ward is answering the violence.”</p>

      <p>Bjorn forced himself upright, but did not take another step. The goblins surged for the opening before Anya cut it shut with two fast strikes and a boot to the lead runner's chest.</p>

      <p>Elara traced the Weave past the frayed threads to where the pattern still held. She left the damaged strands alone. Found the load-bearing seam. Pulled once to loosen, once to turn, once to break the ward's certainty.</p>

      <p>The sanctum's protections shuddered open.</p>

      <p>For one breath, the path stood clear.</p>
    </div>

